# Java Modifier Keywords with Real-Time Examples (Interview Guide)

## 1. `public`

A `public` class, method, or variable is accessible from anywhere in the application.

### Real-Time Example

A REST API endpoint should be accessible to other classes.

```java
public class EmployeeService {

    public void getEmployees() {
        System.out.println("Employee List");
    }
}
```

Usage

```java
EmployeeService service = new EmployeeService();
service.getEmployees();
```

**Use Case:** Spring Boot Controllers and Services expose public methods.

---

## 2. `private`
.............................................
............................................
A `private` member is accessible only within the same class.

### Real-Time Example
.............................................
............................................
Bank account balance should not be modified directly.

```java
public class BankAccount {

    private double balance = 5000;

    public double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }
}
```

Usage

```java
BankAccount account = new BankAccount();

// account.balance = 10000;   // ❌ Compilation Error

System.out.println(account.getBalance());
```

**Use Case:** Protect sensitive fields like password, salary, account balance.

---

## 3. `protected`
.............................................
............................................
Accessible within the same package and by subclasses in other packages.

### Real-Time Example

```java
class Employee {

    protected void calculateBonus() {
        System.out.println("Employee Bonus");
    }
}

class Manager extends Employee {

    public void showBonus() {
        calculateBonus();
    }
}
```

**Use Case:** Parent class functionality shared with child classes.

---

## 4. `static`
.............................................
............................................
Belongs to the class instead of an object.

### Real-Time Example

```java
public class Bank {

    static String bankName = "SBI";
}
```

Usage

```java
System.out.println(Bank.bankName);
```

Every account belongs to the same bank, so only one copy of `bankName` is needed.

Another example:

```java
Math.sqrt(25);
```

`Math.sqrt()` is a static method.

---

## 5. `final`
.............................................
............................................
Prevents modification.

### Final Variable

```java
final double PI = 3.14159;
```

Cannot change:

```java
PI = 3.15; // ❌ Error
```

### Final Method
.............................................
............................................
```java
class Vehicle {

    final void start() {
        System.out.println("Starting...");
    }
}
```

Child classes cannot override `start()`.

### Final Class
.............................................
............................................
```java
final class Utility {
}
```

Cannot be extended.

**Real-Time Example:** `String` is a `final` class to maintain immutability.

---

## 6. `abstract`
.............................................
............................................
Represents incomplete classes or methods.

### Real-Time Example

```java
abstract class Payment {

    abstract void pay();
}

class UpiPayment extends Payment {

    @Override
    void pay() {
        System.out.println("UPI Payment");
    }
}
```

**Use Case:** Different payment methods implement the same operation differently.

---

## 7. `synchronized`
.............................................
............................................
Allows only one thread at a time to execute a method or block.

### Real-Time Banking Example

```java
class BankAccount {

    private int balance = 1000;

    public synchronized void withdraw(int amount) {

        balance -= amount;

        System.out.println("Remaining Balance: " + balance);
    }
}
```

Without `synchronized`, two users withdrawing simultaneously could produce an incorrect balance.

**Use Case:** Banking, ticket booking, inventory management.

---

## 8. `native`
.............................................
............................................
Declares that the method is implemented in another language (typically C/C++).

### Example

```java
public class Printer {

    native void print();
}
```

Implementation is provided using JNI (Java Native Interface).

**Real-Time Use Cases:**

* Camera access
* Bluetooth
* Fingerprint scanners
* Device drivers

---

## 9. `strictfp`
.............................................
............................................
Ensures floating-point calculations produce consistent results across platforms.

### Example

```java
public strictfp class Calculator {

    double calculate() {
        return 10.0 / 3;
    }
}
```

**Real-Time Use Cases:**

* Banking interest calculations
* Scientific applications
* Financial software

> **Note:** As of Java 17, `strictfp` is largely obsolete because floating-point behavior is standardized, but the keyword is still valid.

---

## 10. `transient`
.............................................
............................................
Prevents a field from being serialized.

### Example

```java
import java.io.Serializable;

class User implements Serializable {

    String username;

    transient String password;
}
```

Serialization:
.............................................
............................................
```java
User user = new User();
user.username = "sunil";
user.password = "secret123";
```

After deserialization:

```text
username = sunil
password = null
```

**Real-Time Use Cases:**

* Passwords
* OTPs
* Session tokens
* Credit card CVV

---

## 11. `volatile`
.............................................
............................................
Ensures that changes made by one thread are immediately visible to other threads.

### Example

```java
class Server {

    volatile boolean running = true;

    public void stop() {
        running = false;
    }
}
```

Another thread checking `running` will immediately see the updated value.

**Real-Time Use Cases:**

* Server shutdown flags
* Feature toggles
* Application status indicators
* Thread communication

